default              
defaultHow effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities?  How could Community Transport be improved?
default              
default&#xa0;
defaultWest 
defaultSomerset is fortunate to have nine community car schemes operating in the district, 
defaultrun
default by volunteers, where there is little or no public transport, with the aim of reducing 
defaultindividual isolation and providing
default access to healthcare
default and ensuring
default local familie
defaults’ health needs are met
default, where possible
default.  Accessible Transport West (ATWest
default - 
defaulthttp://www.atwest.org.uk/
default) is a community transport service offering wheelchair and accessible transport to residents of West Somerset. 
default They provide for those who do not have their own transport or cannot access public transport or car scheme
defaults due to lack to availability,
default sickness, age or disability.  The services include a SLINKY ‘dial a ride’ door to door service, a car scheme using vol
defaultunteers own vehicles, Moor Rover
default (taking local people and tourists with their dogs/bikes to the moor to access linear/circular rights of way) (self-financing), six shopping buses to Minehead and one to Williton (full to capacity – no vacancies at present)
default 
defaultand travel club.
default  All users of ATWest services register free of charge and can then access all their services.
default&#xa0;
defaultDue to the increase in retirement age and the need for people to continue to work, our community transport schemes are finding it much harder to
default recruit volunteer drivers; these services may need additional funding in the future to encourage more drivers.
default&#xa0;
default5
default              
defaultTo what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport service?
default&#xa0;
defaultOnly 
defaultthose residents who can afford to pay for taxi services should be expected to rely on this provision
default, particularly taking into consideration the large distances people have to travel to reach our main service areas
default.  Many of our isolated residents are unable to afford the luxury of a taxi service with the added 
defaultchallenge of having an unknown driver.  For some this can be addressed by using community car scheme service (when available) as the driver is usually a loca
defaultl person, who is already known to them
default, thereby reducing their perceived vulnerability
default.
